        "id": 1003211
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-08T10:22:33Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I wonder, if the accessible buckets are known, if it\u0027s faster to do n queries in parallel each restricted with dq.Eq(\"bucket_id\", buckets[i]). It may load too many entities in memory though since there could be up to pageSize * len(buckets) results...\n\nAn alternative in case modifying gae/datastore is infeasible.",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "49696a41_21d5765d",
        "filename": "buildbucket/appengine/internal/search/query.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 214,
      "author": {
        "id": 1398165
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-10T19:58:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yeah, the recent changes in Py says the accessible buckets will always be non-empty even for admins.\n\nIt seems we have three options here. \n1) Keep using the for-loop to find the exact amount of qualified builds in order.\n2) Use n parallel queries here and then sorting.\n3) Use n parallel queries and sorting in gae/datastore.\n\nI lean to the 1st option. The current Py code uses the same for-loop and works well (https://source.chromium.org/chromium/infra/infra/+/aec30d4e667210d2e479b90dd9524c540d93a62b:appengine/cr-buildbucket/search.py;l\u003d61-78). The latency may not be as long as we think. But it couldn\u0027t be quantified now. I\u0027m thinking we keep the for-loop and in the traffic shadowing stage next week, we can measure the performance to decide if it needs to optimize. \n\nFor the option 2) and 3), the downside is as you said it may cost a lot of in-memory usage. Not sure if it\u0027s good to use much more memory vs a longer latency. \nFor 3), it expands the scope and will take more efforts and time as we need to make it generic. Also, if the lib supports IN operator, the OR operator also needs to be supports as the two are the same underlyingly. \n\nConsidering above, I propose to use the option 1. \n\n+nodir@ as the author of python part. What do you think about this?",
      "parentUuid": "440f84cf_095d1180",
      "revId": "3b50bd705fca5dd9f56fc4f3511c8987ae6dbc9f",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
